class CombinationIterator {
    private final List<String> combinations;
    private int index;

    public CombinationIterator(String characters, int combinationLength) {
        combinations = new ArrayList<>();
        generate(characters.toCharArray(), combinationLength, 0, new StringBuilder());
        index = 0;
    }

    private void generate(char[] chars, int len, int start, StringBuilder sb) {
        if (sb.length() == len) {
            combinations.add(sb.toString());
            return;
        }
        for (int i = start; i < chars.length; i++) {
            sb.append(chars[i]);
            generate(chars, len, i + 1, sb);
            sb.setLength(sb.length() - 1);
        }
    }

    public String next() {
        return combinations.get(index++);
    }

    public boolean hasNext() {
        return index < combinations.size();
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(2^n) for constructor, O(1) for next and hasNext
space complexity: O(C(n,k)) where C(n,k) is the number of combinations
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Pre-generate all lexicographically ordered combinations once during construction using backtracking, then serve them in O(1) per call. Memory footprint is bounded by C(15,7)=6435 worst-case, fitting easily within constraints.

